Plamodel‑Style Programming Philosophy
The Original Document of the Outer OS, Grammar Specification, and Black‑Box Architecture
Author: S (Shou)

This document defines the Plamodel‑Style Programming Philosophy,
including the Outer OS, grammar specification, and black‑box architecture.
It serves as the official original source.

1. Background
Modern programming assumes that “writing code” is the default.
But in reality:

Beginners struggle with syntax and environment setup

Experienced developers rewrite the same logic repeatedly

Templates are rigid and non‑extensible

AI now generates massive amounts of code

Language barriers still remain

This structure has reached its limit.

The Plamodel‑Style Philosophy shifts programming from:

“writing code” → “assembling components.”

2. What Is the Plamodel‑Style Approach?
A programming philosophy where:

Programs are built from components (logic units)

Behavior is defined through configuration

Features emerge through combination

Writing code is no longer the goal—
it becomes a tool for assembling components.

3. Problems This Philosophy Solves
For Beginners
Syntax errors block progress

Nothing runs, so learning stalls

For Experienced Developers
Rewriting the same logic

Switching mental models across languages

For the Market
Templates are “finished products” with low extensibility

Logic authorship is not protected

In the AI Era
AI writes code

Humans still learn as if they must write it

The Plamodel‑Style approach solves these issues structurally.

4. Core Structure
4.1 Componentization
Logic is extracted into minimal, reusable, stable components.

4.2 Configuration
Behavior changes through configuration files—
beginners only modify settings.

4.3 Combination
Complex features emerge by combining components,
like assembling a plastic model.

4.4 Rights Structure
Logic authors retain copyright

Users receive usage rights

Viewing rights are separate

Modification requires permission

4.5 Market Structure
Components become assets.
More components → more value → network effects.

4.6 Language Independence
Works across PHP, JavaScript, Python, and more.

4.7 Alignment With the AI Era
AI writes code.
Humans focus on understanding, judging, and assembling.

5. Why Beginners Grow
