9. Formal Definition of the Outer OS
The Outer OS (Outer Structure OS) fixes the program’s grammar externally
while allowing internal logic to be replaced freely.

It consists of three layers:

● parts / flow — Outer Grammar
The application grammar is fixed externally.
No logic is written here.

● model — Receiver Layer
Receives the outer grammar and passes it to the core.

● core — Logic Layer
Executes the actual processing.
Completely separated from the outer grammar.

This enables complete separation of grammar and logic.

10. Black‑Box Architecture
The central concept of the Outer OS.

A black box means:

Internal logic is invisible

public and server are fully separated

Outer layer = grammar only

Inner layer = logic only

External modification is impossible

This ensures security, rights protection, and market viability.

